{"type":"message","id":"7aa71013","parentId":"bd85aed6","timestamp":"2026-04-14T14:29:19.278Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the auto-score-classify hook's event filter:\n\n```javascript\nif (event.type !== \"message\" || event.action !== \"preprocessed\") {\n  return;\n}\n```\n\nIt fires on `type=message, action=preprocessed`. And the session-summary hook fires on:\n\n```javascript\nconst isTarget = event.type === \"command\" && (event.action === \"new\" || event.action === \"reset\");\n```\n\nSo `session-summary` hooks into `type=command, action=new/reset`. But `auto-score-classify` hooks into `type=message, action=preprocessed`.\n\nNow the key question: **What event type/action does OpenClaw actually emit for `/new`?**\n\n\nLooking at the context.json structure, the bootstrap hook in handler.ts listens for `agent:bootstrap` events. This suggests OpenClaw emits different event types depending on the action—bootstrap for initialization, command for session resets, and message for incoming user messages. I need to trace what event actually fires when a user sends `/new`.","thinkingSignature":"769bf233c67fb5c103350d49c0a058cfcaa8d957baab484960b13a082675379e"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_fb92a8b9233a4875a0824f8d","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -rn \"type.*=.*agent\\|action.*=.*bootstrap\\|type.*agent\\|action.*bootstrap\" ~/.openclaw/ --include=\"*.js\" --include=\"*.ts\" 2>/dev/null | grep -v \"node_modules\" | grep -v \".map\" | head -20"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_c1a4c950383140729f2b6074","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -rn \"agent:bootstrap\\|agent:new\\|agent:reset\\|session:new\" ~/.openclaw/ --include=\"*.js\" --include=\"*.ts\" 2>/dev/null | grep -v \"node_modules\" | grep -v \".map\" | grep -v \"handler\" | head -20"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":1393,"output":387,"cacheRead":44800,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":465