{"type":"message","id":"1141420a","parentId":"15eeae86","timestamp":"2026-04-14T14:29:28.320Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so there ARE two different handlers for `agent:bootstrap`:\n1. `memory-bootstrap` skill: `if (event.type !== 'agent' || event.action !== 'bootstrap')`\n2. `hooks/handler.ts` (and `handler.js`): `if (event.type !== 'agent' || event.action !== 'bootstrap')`\n\nBoth check `event.type === 'agent' && event.action === 'bootstrap'`. This is the event that should fire on /new.\n\nBut the `session-summary` hook checks for `event.type === \"command\" && (event.action === \"new\" || event.action === \"reset\")`. These are different event types!\n\nSo there are two separate hooks:\n- `agent:bootstrap` → fires when the agent starts up (for workspace bootstrap files injection) → handler.ts (self-improvement + session-summary bootstrap), memory-bootstrap skill\n\n\n- `command:new/reset` → fires when /new or /reset command is called → session-summary hook\n\nThe `agent:bootstrap` event seems to fire after the agent has started (during LLM initialization), while `command:new/reset` fires when the /new command is issued. I need to trace where these events get emitted in the gateway codebase to understand the actual sequence.","thinkingSignature":"55f0167b3ef0352e52e79f1f4c4ff478fda69b78fe2bb914bae1e1e08ea0963a"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_e553e5f0e9144e4f8c2de3b3","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"find ~/.openclaw -name \"*.js\" -not -path \"*/node_modules/*\" -exec grep -l \"agent:bootstrap\" {} \\; 2>/dev/null"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_ec6652e9f3f348fea1815ace","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls ~/.openclaw/gateway/ 2>/dev/null; ls ~/.openclaw/extensions/ 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":379,"output":364,"cacheRead":46144,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":46887,"cost":{"input":0.0001137,"output":0.0004368,"cacheRead":0.00276863999