{"type":"message","id":"74647ac7","parentId":"44991f92","timestamp":"2026-04-14T14:31:42.905Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the full picture. The `loadInternalHooks` function:\n1. First loads directory-based hooks from workspace/managed/bundled via `loadWorkspaceHookEntries`\n2. Then loads legacy config handlers from `config.hooks.internal.handlers`\n\nFor the session-summary hook to fire, it needs to:\n1. Be discovered as a workspace hook entry (via `loadWorkspaceHookEntries`)\n2. Pass the `shouldIncludeHook` filter\n3. Have a valid handler that gets registered\n\nThe workspace hook entries are loaded from directories. Let me check `loadWorkspaceHookEntries`.\n\nActually, I think the core issue is simpler. The session-summary hook in `~/.openclaw/hooks/session-summary/` is a HOOK.md + handler.js structure. \n\nLooking at the `loadWorkspaceHookEntries` function, it searches for hooks in the workspace directory, managed hooks directory, and bundled hooks directory. So the session-summary hook in `~/.openclaw/hooks/` should be getting discovered and loaded through this mechanism. But then there's the legacy config handlers path that loads from `config.hooks.internal.handlers`, which is separate from the directory-based discovery.\n\nLet me trace through `loadWorkspaceHookEntries` to understand how it actually finds and registers these hooks, since that's where the disconnect might be happening.","thinkingSignature":"03fb1c41ea57c2e63fcde25bf970e7a7d1bef8dca41c37f15192bdbf583de0ac"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_f8198e3039e649769d7bc512","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"loadWorkspaceHookEntries\\|shouldIncludeHook\\|workspace.*hook.*entry\\|hook.*entry.*workspace\" ~/.nvm/versions/node/v22.22.1/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/loader-BSIqIOsD.js 2>/dev/null | head -30"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_66ca5363bdcd4dd38cdbf754","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"shouldIncludeHook\" ~/.nvm/