ntId({\n\t\t\tsessionKey: params.sessionKey,\n\t\t\tconfig: params.cfg\n\t\t})\n\t};\n}\nfunction buildSessionStartHookPayload(params) {\n\treturn {\n\t\tevent: {\n\t\t\tsessionId: params.sessionId,\n\t\t\tsessionKey: params.sessionKey,\n\t\t\tresumedFrom: params.resumedFrom\n\t\t},\n\t\tcontext: buildSessionHookContext({\n\t\t\tsessionId: params.sessionId,\n\t\t\tsessionKey: params.sessionKey,\n\t\t\tcfg: params.cfg\n\t\t})\n\t};\n}\nfunction buildSessionEndHookPayload(params) {\n\treturn {\n\t\tevent: {\n\t\t\tsessionId: params.sessionId,\n\t\t\tsessionKey: params.sessionKey,\n\t\t\tmessageCount: params.messageCount ?? 0,\n\t\t\tdurationMs: params.durationMs,\n\t\t\treason: params.reason,\n\t\t\tsessionFile: params.sessionFile,\n\t\t\ttranscriptArchived: params.transcriptArchived,\n\t\t\tnextSessionId: params.nextSessionId,\n\t\t\tnextSessionKey: params.nextSessionKey\n\t\t},\n\t\tcontext: buildSessionHookContext({\n\t\t\tsessionId: params.sessionId,\n\t\t\tsessionKey: params.sessionKey,\n\t\t\tcfg: params.cfg\n\t\t})\n\t};\n}\n//#endregion\nexport { buildSessionStartHookPayload as n, buildSessionEndHookPayload as t };","cwd":"/home/ai/.openclaw/workspace/main"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1776177346669}}
{"type":"message","id":"6ac5de6f","parentId":"24abddec","timestamp":"2026-04-14T14:36:33.424Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the full picture. Let me analyze:\n\n1. **`session_start` hook** - Built by `session-updates-BU9ULY8h.js`, fired via `runSessionStart` from `session-updates-BU9ULY8h.js:63`. It calls `buildSessionStartHookPayload` from `session-hooks-TpmBubJz.js`.\n\nLooking at `buildSessionStartHookPayload`:\n```js\nfunction buildSessionStartHookPayload(params) {\n    return {\n        event: {\n            sessionId: params.sessionId,\n            sessionKey: params.sessionKey,\n            resumedFrom: params.resumedFrom\n        },\n        context: buildSessionHookContext({...})\n    };\n}\n```\n\nThe `event` here has `sessionId`, `sessionKey`, `resumedFrom` — but **NO `type` or `action` fields**! So when `session_start` hook handlers check `event.type === \"agent\" && event.action === \"bootstrap\"`, they will **never match**, because the event structure is completely different.\n\nThis is the root cause. The `session_summary` hook's `HOOK.md` says:\n```yaml\nevents:\n  - agent:bootstrap\n```\n\nBut the `session_start` event that's actually fired has a completely different structure:\n```js\n{\n    sessionId: ...,\n    sessionKey: ...,\n    resumedFrom: ...\n}\n```\n\nAnd the `agent:bootstrap` event has:\n```js\n{\n    type: \"agent\",\n    action: \"bootstrap\",\n    sessionKey: ...,\n    context: {\n        workspaceDir: ...,\n        bootstrapFiles: [...],\n        ...\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThese are **completely different event types**. The `session-summary` hook is listening for `agent:bootstrap` but `session_start` doesn't fire that type.\n\n2. **When does `agent:bootstrap` fire?** From `bootstrap-budget-BZw4htx0.js`, it fires when `resolveBootstrapFilesForRun` is called. This happens during the run preparation (in `pi-embedded-Vw-lS5ti.js` or `prompt-select-styled-BfACiVO5.js`), which is AFTER the session_start hook fires.\n\nThe `agent:bootstrap` hook gets triggered inside `applyBootstrapHookOverrides` within `resolveBootstrapFilesForRun`, which is part of the bootstrap context resolution that happens during prompt building. Meanwhile, `session_start` fires earlier from `session-updates-BU9ULY8h.js` without any `agent:bootstrap` event, so the two hooks are operating at different stages of the session lifecycle.\n\n3. **The real problem**: The `session-summary` hook is registered for `agent:bootstrap` events, but it's trying to read session files that may not exist yet or are in the wrong location for webchat sessions. The hook needs to capture the session state at the right moment, but the event timing and file resolution are misaligned.\n\nLooking at the event registration, `session_start` doesn't use `agent:bootstrap` at all—it has its own event type. So `session-summary` is listening for the wrong event. When `session_start` fires, the handler checks `event.type === \"agent\" && event.action === \"bootstrap\"`, but the actual event structure is completely different. The issue is that `session_summary` is registered for `agent:bootstrap` when it should be listening to whatever event `session_start` actually emits.\n\nThe ephemeral capture works because it hooks into `message_sent` and `message_received` events, but `session-summary` needs something that fires at the right moment—probably `session_start` or `session_end`—to write the session summary to disk. The bootstrap hook then needs to read that file and inject it into context, but that's where the chain breaks down. is that `session-summary` should listen for `session_start` instead of `agent:bootstrap`. When a new session begins, `session_start` fires during the very first run preparation, and `resolveBootstrapContextForRun` gets called then too. So if `session-summary` hooks into `session_start`, it can write the summary file before `resolveBootstrapContextForRun` tries to read it. This would establish the correct sequence: `session_start` triggers the summary write, then the bootstrap context resolution picks it up on that same first turn.\n\nBut there's a timing issue—`resolveBootstrapContextForRun` gets invoked during prompt building, which happens before the agent actually runs. So when the session summary hook fires on `session_start`, it might execute after the bootstrap context has already been resolved for that first turn, creating a race condition where the summary isn't available when needed.\n\nThe real problem is that session summaries are session-level metadata, not turn-level. They're written once per session but read once per turn to maintain continuity. The current implementation is trying to do this at the wrong point in the lifecycle.\n\nI should write the summary at `session_end` instead—that's when the session is truly complete and all the data is final. Then `session_start` can simply read the most recent summary from the previous session and inject it as a bootstrap file. This avoids the race condition entirely since the write happens after all turns are complete.\n\nBut there's a complication: the first turn of a new session needs the previous session's summary, and that write only happens at `session_end`. So on the very first turn, there's no summary yet to inject. The summary gets written after the session ends, which means it's only available from the second turn onward.\n\nThis is actually fine—the session summary is meant to preserve continuity from earlier sessions, so having it starting from turn 2 is the right behavior. The `session_start` hook should read the latest available summary from disk and inject it as a bootstrap file.\n\nThe event structure mismatch between what `session-summary` hook expects and what `session_start` actually provides is blocking this from working. Once that's corrected, the flow becomes: when a new session starts, `session_start` finds the most recent summary file from the previous session and makes it available to the bootstrap context, so the agent can reference it on that first turn.\n\nBut there's a timing issue—by the time `session_start` fires, `resolveBootstrapContextForRun` has already run for this session's first turn, so even with the fix, the summary won't be available until the second turn. To get it working on the first turn, I'd need to inject it earlier in the lifecycle, before the initial bootstrap context is resolved. Looking at the event structure, `session_start` doesn't include `type` or `action` fields, which is the core mismatch. The event only carries `sessionId`, `sessionKey`, and `resumedFrom` - completely different from what `agent:bootstrap` provides. This means `session-summary` is listening for the wrong event entirely.\n\nLooking at the bootstrap hook code, it checks `event.type === 'agent' && event.action === 'bootstrap'`, but the actual event structure doesn't support this pattern. The `event.type` field itself isn't even defined in the `session_start` event structure, so there's a fundamental API mismatch here. The real issue is that `session_start` events never trigger the `agent:bootstrap` handler, so the bootstrap hook never runs. The bootstrap hook is actually invoked during `resolveBootstrapContextForRun`, which happens after the session starts. But the `session_start` event itself doesn't trigger the bootstrap hook—it fires at the session level, not during the bootstrap phase.\n\nSo the actual sequence is: `session_start` runs first, then the session processes messages, and only much later (when the session ends or compaction occurs) does the bootstrap hook get involved. This means the bootstrap hook is fundamentally misaligned with where it should be injected if the goal is to provide context at the start of a new session. a session. But the summary file for the *current* session won't exist yet—it only gets created after the session ends. So what gets injected during the first turn?\n\nLooking at the actual flow more carefully: `session_start` fires at the beginning of each session, and at that point, the *previous* session's summary file is the most recent one available. The bootstrap hook reads that file and injects it, which gives the agent context about what was discussed before. Then throughout the current session, the ephemeral hook continuously captures the conversation, and when the session ends, `session_end` (or `before_reset`) writes out a new summary file for just-completed session. That file sits dormant until the *next* session starts, when it becomes the \"previous session summary\" that gets injected. So the chain is really: previous session's summary → inject at start of next session → capture current session → write summary at end → repeat.\n\nThe issue is that `session-summary` is listening for `agent:bootstrap` instead of `session_start`. The `session_start` event does fire and the hook runner has a handler for it, but the event structure doesn't match what the bootstrap hook expects, so nothing actually runs.\n\nI need to fix the hook to listen for the correct event and update its handler logic to work with the `session_start` payload. The core issue is that `session-summary` is listening for the wrong event type—`agent:bootstrap` instead of `session_start`. The bootstrap hook does run, but only much later during prompt building, which is too late for session-start operations.\n\nThe fix requires updating `session-summary`'s hook configuration to listen for `session_start`, then ensuring the handler reads the latest summary file from the previous session. However, there's a timing constraint: since the summary file for the current session won't exist until it ends, only the previous session's summary is available on the first turn.\n\nLooking at the actual `bootstrap-budget-BZw4htx0.js` code, `applyBootstrapHookOverrides` is called within `resolveBootstrapFilesForRun`, which gets invoked during prompt building. At that point, `bootstrapFiles` are already loaded from disk, and the hook just modifies them in memory. The hook can't create new bootstrap files from scratch—it can only filter or transform existing ones. So if the goal is to inject a session summary, that summary needs to already exist as a file before the hook runs.\n\nThe core problem is that session summaries are written after sessions end, but we'd want them available at the start of the next session. There's fundamentally a timing mismatch here—the summary for session N can only be created after session N ends, which means it's only accessible when session N+1 begins. This suggests the session summary approach might not be the right mechanism for what we're trying to accomplish.\n\nLooking at the memory pipeline more carefully, the actual flow seems to be that `ephemeral` captures each turn, then at some point a session summary gets created, and the bootstrap hook injects it. The question is whether this happens at the right time in the session lifecycle, and whether there's a way to make the summary available earlier or if we need to accept this inherent delay.\n\nThe most straightforward fix would be to ensure the session summary hook is properly listening for the right events—either `session_start` or the appropriate bootstrap trigger—so it can inject the summary when the session initializes, rather than relying on it being available at the exact moment we need it. I need to trace through when `applyBootstrapHookOverrides` actually fires relative to the session lifecycle. Looking at the execution flow, `resolveBootstrapContextForRun` gets called during prompt building, which happens before the agent processes any user message. If the hook is supposed to inject session summaries at session start, it needs to run at that point—not after the first response when the session is already underway.\n\nThe core issue is that `session-summary` is listening for the wrong event. It's watching for `agent:bootstrap` when it should be watching for `session_start` or `session_end`. The bootstrap hook that runs during prompt building is too late in the flow to capture the session initialization properly.\n\nBefore implementing a fix, I should verify whether there are other event types that fire earlier in the session lifecycle that I'm missing.","thinkingSignature":"f1f56ab6c105d2fa056890ab58d53b4ab9ff1f30f4bf5fad5d2c1dec39b47f6e"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_f16208648f634ac38b40029f","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"triggerInternalHook\\|createInternalHookEvent.*"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_b1e10678d76744c6874877d3","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"runBeforeReset\\|before_reset\\|runSessionEnd\\|runSessionStart\" ~/.nvm/versions/node/v22.22.1/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/session-updates-BU9ULY8h.js 2>/dev/null | head -30"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":541,"output":2654,"cacheRead":45824,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":49019,"cost":{"input":0.0001623,"output":0.0031848,"cacheRead":0.0027494399999999997,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.006096539999999999}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776177346673,"responseId":"062d83c2f608b2772a0e075b0a7071b8"}}
