{"type":"message","id":"f8f6e0fe","parentId":"2af9d624","timestamp":"2026-04-14T14:40:59.983Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `resolveHookKey` function returns `entry?.metadata?.hookKey ?? hookName`. If no `hookKey` in metadata, it uses the hook name from HOOK.md frontmatter.\n\nFor session-summary hook, the name is \"session-summary\" in the frontmatter. So the config key would be `\"session-summary\"`. And in `openclaw.json` we have `\"session-summary\": { \"enabled\": true }`. This matches!\n\nNow let me look at `resolveHookEnableState` more carefully:\n\n```js\nfunction resolveHookEnableState(params) {\n    const { entry, config } = params;\n    const hookKey = resolveHookKey(entry.hook.name, entry);\n    const hookConfig = params.hookConfig ?? resolveHookConfig(config, hookKey);\n    if (entry.hook.source === \"openclaw-plugin\") return { enabled: true };\n    if (hookConfig?.enabled === false) return { enabled: false, reason: \"disabled in config\" };\n    if (getHookSourcePolicy(entry.hook.source).defaultEnableMode === \"explicit-opt-in\" && hookConfig?.enabled !== true) return { enabled: false, reason: \"workspace hook (disabled by default)\" };\n    return { enabled: true };\n}\n```\n\nFor `openclaw-managed` source, `defaultEnableMode` is \"default-on\", not \"explicit-opt-in\". So the \"workspace hook (disabled by default)\" check only applies to `openclaw-workspace`. For `openclaw-managed`, it's automatically enabled unless `hookConfig?.enabled === false`.\n\nThe hook is `\"openclaw-managed\"` source. The config has `\"session-summary\": { \"enabled\": true }`. So:\n1. `hookConfig?.enabled` = true → not false\n2. `defaultEnableMode` for `openclaw-managed` is \"default-on\" → doesn't match \"explicit-opt-in\"\n\nSo `shouldIncludeHook` should return true. The hook should be loaded and enabled.\n\nThen why isn't it working? Let me think about what could go wrong:\n\n1. **Event is triggered**: `emitResetCommandHooks` calls `createInternalHookEvent(\"command\", params.action, ...)` and `triggerInternalHook(hookEvent)`\n2. **Handler is registered**: `registerInternalHook(\"command:new\", handler)` is called during hook loading\n3. **triggerInternalHook** dispatches to all handlers for `\"command:new\"`\n\nBut wait - there might be a timing issue. Looking at the internal-hooks file again, I need to understand how the handler registration and event triggering actually work. The hook system creates the event and dispatches it, but maybe the handler isn't being found at that point.\n\nActually, I think I found it. When `session-summary` hook is loaded, it calls `registerInternalHook(\"command:new\", handler)`. The `session-summary` handler does async work (reading session files, calling LLM, writing summaries), but it returns `void` (not a Promise). The `triggerInternalHook` function awaits each handler, but since the handler returns `void`, it resolves immediately without waiting for the actual async work to complete. The hook fire-and-forget design might be causing issues if the handler is trying to do async operations that aren't being properly awaited. The handler function itself is not async - it just calls `run(event).catch(...)`. So it returns `undefined` immediately when called.\n\nThen `triggerInternalHook` does:\n```js\nfor (const handler of allHandlers) try {\n    await handler(event);\n} catch (err) { ... }\n```\n\nSince `handler` is not async and returns `undefined`, `await undefined` resolves immediately. The `.catch()` on the returned promise handles errors from the `run()` promise.\n\nSo the handler is invoked, `run()` starts in background via `.catch()` - fire and forget.\n\nThis seems correct. The session-summary handler should be called when `/new` fires.\n\nWait, maybe the issue is that when I do `/new` in webchat, the `emitResetCommandHooks` function is called but it creates the event with `sessionKey` from `params.sessionKey ?? \"\"`. For webchat sessions, maybe the sessionKey is empty or different, so the hook gets an event with empty sessionKey and the handler might not work properly.\n\nActually no - the sessionKey in the event is just for the hook to know which session it is. It doesn't affect the hook logic.\n\nLet me think about what could actually be going wrong...\n\nI should check if there are any errors in the gateway logs. Actually, I can't easily access those. Let me try a different approach - let me manually trigger a `/new` command and see if the session-summary hook creates a file.\n\nBut wait - the user is asking \"链路跑通了吗\" - \"Did the chain run through?\" referring to the bootstrap→session-summary bootstrap injection chain. From the context, this is about whether the session-summary file created at the end of a session gets picked up as a bootstrap file when the next session starts.\n\nFrom my investigation:\n1. ✅ `session-summary` hook is registered (correct source, correct config)\n2. ✅ `handler.js` has the right code\n3. ✅ The hook fires on `command:new` and `command:reset` events\n4. ❓ But: when `/new` is executed, does `emitResetCommandHooks` actually get called for webchat?\n\nI think the real question is whether the session-summary file, once created, actually gets injected as a bootstrap file when the next session starts. That's the missing piece - I need to verify if that bootstrap injection path is working.","thinkingSignature":"1b124b8a01f8b62c29dd27f5c615c728ac45beba999236a919db2e61da97b619"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_40ef47ed06534aaabc684bdf","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls -la ~/.openclaw/workspace/main/memory/*session-summary* 2>/dev/null; ls -la ~/.openclaw/memory/*session-summary* 2>/dev/null; echo \"---check ephemeral---\"; ls -la ~/.openclaw/workspace/main/memory/ephemeral/ 2>/dev/null; ls -la ~/.openclaw/memory/ephemeral/ 2>/dev/null"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_0572ee718db24be9a8574b2f","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Check the current session summary files -