{"type":"message","id":"c01a6256","parentId":"3be4d2c4","timestamp":"2026-04-14T14:43:46.436Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_757a1c72a438400fbb6986cc","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"const osRaw = resolveOpenClawManifestOs(metadataObj);\n\tconst eventsRaw = normalizeStringList(metadataObj.events);\n\treturn {\n\t\talways: typeof metadataObj.always === \"boolean\" ? metadataObj.always : void 0,\n\t\temoji: readStringValue(metadataObj.emoji),\n\t\thomepage: readStringValue(metadataObj.homepage),\n\t\thookKey: readStringValue(metadataObj.hookKey),\n\t\texport: readStringValue(metadataObj.export),\n\t\tos: osRaw.length > 0 ? osRaw : void 0,\n\t\tevents: eventsRaw.length > 0 ? eventsRaw : [],\n\t\trequires,\n\t\tinstall: install.length > 0 ? install : void 0\n\t};\n}\nfunction resolveHookInvocationPolicy(frontmatter) {\n\treturn { enabled: parseFrontmatterBool(getFrontmatterString(frontmatter, \"enabled\"), true) };\n}\nfunction resolveHookKey(hookName, entry) {\n\treturn entry?.metadata?.hookKey ?? hookName;\n}\n//#endregion\nexport { resolveOpenClawMetadata as i, resolveHookInvocationPolicy as n, resolveHookKey as r, parseFrontmatter as t };"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":47,"aggregated":"const osRaw = resolveOpenClawManifestOs(metadataObj);\n\tconst eventsRaw = normalizeStringList(metadataObj.events);\n\treturn {\n\t\talways: typeof metadataObj.always === \"boolean\" ? metadataObj.always : void 0,\n\t\temoji: readStringValue(metadataObj.emoji),\n\t\thomepage: readStringValue(metadataObj.homepage),\n\t\thookKey: readStringValue(metadataObj.hookKey),\n\t\texport: readStringValue(metadataObj.export),\n\t\tos: osRaw.length > 0 ? osRaw : void 0,\n\t\tevents: eventsRaw.length > 0 ? eventsRaw : [],\n\t\trequires,\n\t\tinstall: install.length > 0 ? install : void 0\n\t};\n}\nfunction resolveHookInvocationPolicy(frontmatter) {\n\treturn { enabled: parseFrontmatterBool(getFrontmatterString(frontmatter, \"enabled\"), true) };\n}\nfunction resolveHookKey(hookName, entry) {\n\treturn entry?.metadata?.hookKey ?? hookName;\n}\n//#endregion\nexport { resolveOpenClawMetadata as i, resolveHookInvocationPolicy as n, resolveHookKey as r, parseFrontmatter as t };","cwd":"/home/ai/.openclaw/workspace/main"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1776177826433}}
{"type":"message","id":"b7978a71","parentId":"c01a6256","timestamp":"2026-04-14T14:44:09.235Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the full picture. Let me verify the last piece - why `auto-score-classify` works but `session-summary` doesn't, even though both are in `~/.openclaw/hooks/` (managed hooks dir).\n\nThe key difference: `auto-score-classify` has `always: true` in its metadata, which means it bypasses the `evaluateRuntimeEligibility` check. `session-summary` doesn't have `always: true`.\n\nBut wait - the `evaluateRuntimeEligibility` checks `requires.bins` (node) which should pass... unless there's something else.\n\nActually wait - let me re-read the `evaluateRuntimeEligibility` function:\n\n```javascript\nfunction evaluateRuntimeEligibility(params) {\n    const osList = params.os ?? [];\n    const remotePlatforms = params.remotePlatforms ?? [];\n    if (osList.length > 0 && !osList.includes(resolveRuntimePlatform()) && !remotePlatforms.some((platform) => osList.includes(platform))) return false;\n    if (params.always === true) return true;\n    return evaluateRuntimeRequires({\n        requires: params.requires,\n        ...\n    });\n}\n```\n\nIf `always === true`, it returns `true` immediately, skipping the `requires` check. But `session-summary` doesn't have `always: true`, so it goes to `evaluateRuntimeRequires`.\n\nIn `evaluateRuntimeRequires`:\n```javascript\nconst requiredBins = requires.bins ?? [];\nif (requiredBins.length > 0) for (const bin of requiredBins) {\n    if (params.hasBin(bin)) continue;  // node is found, so this continues\n    if (params.hasRemoteBin?.(bin)) continue;  // no remote bin\n    return false;  // only reached if node NOT found\n}\n```\n\nSo if `node` is in PATH, `hasBin('node')` returns true, and the function continues through all required bins without returning false. This means `session-summary` should pass the runtime eligibility check.\n\nThe `requires` object in the frontmatter specifies `bins: [\"node\"]` and an empty `config` array. Since node is available, the eligibility check succeeds. But the hook still isn't firing on `command:new` events, so something else must be preventing the event from triggering.\n\nLooking at the session-summary hook's event registration - it's listening for `command:new` and `command:reset`. But `auto-score-classify` registers for `message:preprocessed`. If the gateway has a hook registered for `command:new` via `registerInternalHook`, it should fire when `createInternalHookEvent(\"command\", \"new\", ...)` is called in `emitResetCommandHooks`. The event creation and hook registration seem to align, so the issue might be in how the hook is actually being invoked or matched during the reset command. The `triggerInternalHook` function fires handlers registered for both the general `command` type and the specific `command:new` action. So a handler registered for `command:new` will trigger when that event fires, but so would a handler registered just for `command` if it exists. This dual-matching is important because it means the system checks both the broad and specific event categories when triggering handlers.\n\nLooking at `emitResetCommandHooks`, the `hookEvent` is created with type `\"command\"` and action `\"new\"`, which means any handler listening to either `\"command\"` or `\"command:new\"` will execute. The session-summary hook appears to be registered for `command:new` based on the `isTarget` check, so it should fire when the event matches.\n\nBut examining the internal-hooks system more closely, the comment indicates handlers should be registered for the specific event pattern like `command:new`. This suggests the registration and triggering mechanisms might be using different event key formats - one might use the full `command:new` format while the other expects just the base type with the action as a separate parameter. When `triggerInternalHook` receives an event with type `\"command\"` and action `\"new\"`, it constructs the specific key as `\"command:new\"` to find handlers registered for that exact combination. If no handlers are registered for `\"command:new\"`, the function returns early without invoking anything. This means handlers must register with the full `\"type:action\"` format to receive targeted events.\n\nHowever, handlers registered only for the general `\"command\"` type would never match because `triggerInternalHook` never constructs a general-only key—it always builds the specific one. So the issue is that the internal-hooks system expects handlers to explicitly register for the complete event key, not just the type alone. the handler was registered for `\"command\"` instead, it would also match since the event has `type === \"command\"` in the type handlers list.\n\nThe core issue seems to be that `session-summary` isn't firing when expected. But `auto-score-classify` works fine with the same hook loading mechanism, suggesting the problem isn't with the hook system itself. Rather than continue tracing through the event matching logic, I should focus on whether this is actually a webchat-specific issue—checking if the webchat sessions are stored differently or if there's a command event handler unique to that channel.","thinkingSignature":"b909d50040f25ad3ae06c1cc26cbe2299b1ee2ca7e2a7a3fa079477825f29415"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_fc34ca2dd5ab46ffab749a4b","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Check the commands log for the /new event to see what was emitted\ntail -20 ~/.openclaw/logs/commands.log 2>/dev/null"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_3b625a96e13c4c078adc4d7d","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Let's verify the current session's context.json has auto-score-classify running\n# (which proves hooks work in general)\ncat ~/.openclaw/sessions/agent:main:main/context.json 2>/dev/null | python3 -m json.tool 2>/dev/null | head -20"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":382,"output":1204,"cacheRead":72000,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":73586,"cost":{"input":0.0001146,"output":0.0014448,"cacheRead":0.004319999999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.005879399999999999}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776177826438,"responseId":"062d85a257704bd99d0904b51b2d551f"}}
