{"type":"message","id":"3fde74ba","parentId":"ba348c33","timestamp":"2026-04-14T14:44:41.290Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The auto-score-classify hook IS running (context.json has classification/scoring data), but the session-summary hook didn't run. This is the key finding.\n\nBoth hooks are in the same directory (`~/.openclaw/hooks/`), both are loaded from the same managed hooks directory. The auto-score-classify hook fires on `message:preprocessed` event, while session-summary fires on `command:new` and `command:reset`.\n\nSo the issue is NOT hook loading. Both hooks are loaded. The issue is either:\n1. The `command:new` event isn't being registered correctly for the session-summary hook\n2. Or the event is being triggered but the handler has an issue\n\nActually wait - looking at the auto-score-classify metadata:\n```json\n\"events\": [\"message:preprocessed\"],\n\"always\": true\n```\n\nAnd session-summary:\n```json\n\"events\": [\"command:new\", \"command:reset\"],\n\"always\": true\n```\n\nBoth have `always: true` which means they bypass the `evaluateRuntimeEligibility` check. So both should be enabled.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The `message:preprocessed` event fires for every inbound message, so auto-score-classify definitely runs. But the session-summary hook only fires on `/new` or `/reset`.\n\nThe last `/new` was at `2026-04-14 14:23:48.832Z`. But the current session started at around 22:23 (GMT+8), which is 14:23 UTC. So that timestamp matches!\n\nLet me check if maybe the session-summary handler errored out silently. Let me look at the handler error handling.\n\nActually wait - the commands.log entry for the /new at 14:23:48 shows the action was \"new\" from \"openclaw-control-ui\" webchat. But the session key was \"agent:main:main\". The `emitResetCommandHooks` function calls `createInternalHookEvent(\"command\", params.action, params.sessionKey ?? \"\", {...})`.\n \nI need to trace through the actual code flow more carefully. When a `/new` command is issued, the `emitResetCommandHooks` function creates an event with `type=\"command\"` and `action=\"new\"`, then calls `triggerInternalHook` to fire all registered handlers for that event type. The session-summary hook should be listening for this event, but something seems off with how the handlers are being invoked or how the event context is being passed. The session-summary hook handler checks if `event.type === \"command\"` and `event.action === \"new\" || event.action === \"reset\"`, which should match the incoming event. However, there's a potential issue with the `await` in `emitResetCommandHooks` - if `triggerInternalHook` is actually synchronous despite being labeled as async, the hooks might not be completing before the function returns.\n\nLooking at `triggerInternalHook` itself, it's an async function that calls handlers with `await`, but since `run()` isn't awaited in the handler export, the function could return before hooks finish executing. Yet this shouldn't prevent the hooks from running at all.\n\nI should probably add debug logging to see what's actually being passed to these hooks. Actually, I'm wondering if there's a timing issue with how `session-memory` and `command-logger` internal hooks are configured versus the `session-summary` workspace hook. Both register for the same events, so there might be some interaction I'm missing.\n\nLet me reconsider the event flow more carefully. When `/new` executes, it creates a `command:new` internal event that should trigger `session-summary`. The event gets passed to all registered handlers, including the workspace hook. I need to trace through `emitResetCommandHooks` to see what context is actually being sent.\n\nLooking at the context object, it includes `workspaceDir`, but I should verify whether `OPENCLAW_WORKSPACE_DIR` is properly set in the gateway's environment when the handler runs. Without that environment variable, `resolveSessionFile` would fall back to constructing the path using `os.homedir()`, which might not match the actual workspace directory being used.\n\nSince `auto-score-classify` works correctly, that suggests the environment is configured properly for at least some hooks. But there's another possibility I'm noticing: the workspace hook system might be loading hooks from `~/.openclaw/workspace/main/hooks/` rather than the global `~/.openclaw/hooks/` directory. If the session-summary hook isn't in the right location, it wouldn't be loaded even if the configuration is correct.\n\nLet me trace through the `triggerInternalHook` function more carefully. It retrieves handlers for both the general event type and the specific type:action combination, then executes them sequentially. I should verify whether the session-summary hook is actually being registered and triggered.\n\nThe handler lookup is case-sensitive and relies on exact string matching, so if the event type or action doesn't align precisely with how handlers are registered, the hook wouldn't fire. I should also consider whether the hook is being registered under one name but called under another, or if there's a mismatch in how the event object is structured versus what the handler expects.\n\nSince the hook worked before and has `\"always\": true` in its metadata, it should bypass eligibility checks and load regardless. The fact that it's not working now suggests either the gateway didn't reload properly after the last update, or there's something else preventing the hook from being discovered or triggered. I should verify the gateway process is actually running the updated code, and check whether `openclaw gateway status` reveals anything useful about the hook state.\n\nLet me restart the gateway and test the `/new` command to see if the hook fires. But actually, I should reconsider whether `session-summary` was ever functioning correctly. Looking back at the session notes, it appears the hook was created but the bootstrap chain was never fully working—the session-summary file wasn't being found during startup. There was mention of a session-summary hook file existing with the correct naming pattern and `pruneOldSummaries(30)` function, but that was from an earlier implementation.\n\nThe real issue seems to be that when a new session starts via `/new`, the bootstrap event fires and `handler.js` should inject the previous session summary, but this never actually happened. The session-summary hook never generated a file because it was blocked on something, and the bootstrap hook couldn't find what wasn't there to begin with. The gateway was restarted at 19:30 after the hook was updated, so it should be running the latest code. But let me think about whether there's a code issue I'm missing.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the problem from scratch. The core issue is that when `/new` is triggered, the `session-summary` hook doesn't fire. Rather than getting stuck in gateway debugging, I should verify the actual event flow: `emitResetCommandHooks` receives the `/new` command, fires the `command:new` event, which should invoke all registered handlers including `session-summary`. The hook handler runs and calls `writeSummaryFile`, which should create the session-summary file. I need to check whether `writeSummaryFile` is actually being invoked or if something's failing silently.\n\nSince I can't add debug output to the gateway directly, let me trace through the handler's logic more carefully. The handler checks for `event.type === \"command\"` and `event.action === \"new\"`, which should match. But what if `workspaceDir` isn't being set correctly in the event context? That would cause `resolveSessionFile` to fail when trying to access `event.context.workspaceDir`, and then it would fall back to constructing a path with `os.homedir()` instead of using the actual workspace directory.\n\nThe real issue might be that the gateway isn't loading the updated hook code at all. The gateway started at 19:30 today, but the session-summary handler was modified at 21:42. I need to figure out if the gateway is using a cached version of the hooks or if it's actually loading from the filesystem.\n\nLet me restart the gateway to force it to reload the hooks, then trigger a new session to see if the hook fires properly. If the hook still doesn't work after a restart, that would confirm the gateway isn't picking up the changes.","thinkingSignature":"a3ee097f4f5a277daad8609b06821640b71f620adbb0232af688e46746e0e95d"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_fcbda529f54548c6ad0eb203","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Verify auto-score-classify is actually running (it wrote context.json)\n# vs session-summary which should have written a session-summary file but didn't\nls -la ~/.openclaw/workspace/main/memory/*session-summary* 2>/dev/null; echo \"---\"\n# Also check the most recent context.json to confirm hooks are running\nstat ~/.openclaw/sessions/agent:main:main/context.json 2>/dev/null | head -5"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_5da3cfda8b194f8a9e93bd68","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# The gateway last started at 19:30 Apr 14, but session-summary handler was modified at 21:42\n# Need to restart to load the new handler\n# First check current gateway status\nopenclaw gateway status 2>&1 | head -10"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":1266,"output":1870,"cacheRead":72320,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":75456,"cost":{"input":0.00037979999999999996,"output":0.002244,"cacheRead":0.0043392,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.006963}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776177849341,"responseId":"062d85b8a35ed1112f74c1145200be70"}}
