{"type":"message","id":"1d3f25c4","parentId":"83078bdb","timestamp":"2026-04-14T14:45:21.139Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The gateway status command is still running. Let me kill it and check if we can use the openclaw CLI to manage hooks.\n\nActually, looking at the context more carefully - the session-summary handler.js was last modified at 21:42 today. But the gateway process started at 19:30 today (before the handler was updated). So the OLD handler is loaded. This means the session-summary hook might have been running with the old code.\n\nBut wait - the old handler also had the same `command:new` / `command:reset` trigger. So even with the old code, the hook should have fired. But no session-summary file was created.\n \nThe old code's session file resolution was likely broken for webchat sessions, and even if it had generated a summary, it would have been written before the gateway started - so any output would be from the old process running before 19:30. Plus, the bootstrap handler reads from `memory/*session-summary*` files, but the session-summary hook writes to `memory/` with a timestamp prefix, so there's a mismatch in what gets read versus what gets written.\n\nLooking at the bootstrap handler code, it filters for files matching `*-session-summary.md`, which should catch files like `2026-04-14-session-summary-xxx.md`. But the old handler's write logic has a slug function that might not be generating the right filename format, and I need to verify what the `writeSummaryFile` function is actually producing.\n\nThe core issue is that we don't know if the old handler ever successfully wrote a session-summary file today. I should just restart the gateway to load the updated handler code and see if that fixes the chain. But I also need to verify that the new handler code properly handles the bootstrap `agent:bootstrap` event, since the `triggerInternalHook` call in `applyBootstrapHookOverrides` might not be working as expected with the session-summary hook listening for `command:new`.\n\nLooking at the event flow more carefully - when `/new` executes, it fires `command:new` which triggers the session-summary hook to generate and write the summary file. Then `agent:bootstrap` fires with the updated `bootstrapFiles` array. So the event sequence should be: `/new` → `command:new` → session-summary writes file → `agent:bootstrap` → bootstrap hook reads the file. This should theoretically work, but I need to confirm the session-summary hook is actually generating the file correctly.","thinkingSignature":"088d21ff6ea0649312a45b1d0ee35d64b9e5532ae86b03ee704379db75786278"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_aa9bd30946e246c88b50a2ea","name":"process","arguments":{"action":"kill","sessionId":"calm-pine"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":399,"output":544,"cacheRead":74176,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":75119,"cost":{"input":0.0001197,"output":0.0006527999999999999,"cacheRead":0.004450559999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.005223059999999999}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776177907378,"responseId":"062d85f2a932ea8112d74d0fa7c0e5be"}}
