{"type":"message","id":"482dd128","parentId":"75f06ae1","timestamp":"2026-04-14T15:02:46.933Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see two files:\n1. `2026-04-14-session-summary-assistant.md` - from my manual test with the real session\n2. `2026-04-14-session-summary-无会话内容.md` - from the previous test with mock sessionBoth have issues - the first one has \"assistant:\" as the topic (extracted from the first assistant message), and the second one says \"(无会话内容)\".The real session file has 400 lines but the handler is reading it wrong. Let me check the extractMessages function - it should extract meaningful content.The issue is that the session file (jsonl) has entries like:\n```json\n{\"type\": \"message\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"[Tue 2026-04-14 22:25 GMT+8] 链路跑通了吗\"}}\n\n\n```\nAnd:\n```json\n{\"type\": \"message\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": \"...some text...\"}}\n```\n\nThe extractMessages function skips lines starting with \"/\" and only takes the first 40 entries from each role type. Since this session is from the Apr 14 22:23 introduction, the first user message would be the initial greeting. The issue might be that the session is large and the function is reading it correctly, but the first meaningful user message is getting lost or malformed.\n\nThe content \"assistant:\" appearing as the topic suggests the first assistant message in the file has role \"assistant\" but no actual content, so it defaults to showing just the role name. I should verify whether the extractMessages function is properly filtering and parsing these JSON entries, since the session file structure looks correct but the extracted topic is wrong.\n```","thinkingSignature":"eaab288de42270dcd0ee4c5f98737fc3c09fe1ad08e72cb0396481176f4ff5b5"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_259437ab84d14194ada457d3","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Clean up test files\nrm -f ~/.openclaw/workspace/main/memory/2026-04-